window.docContents[50].resolve({"/Analytic-Number-Theory/Dirichlet___s-theorem-on-primes-in-arithmetic-progressions/#AINTLIB-___-An-Atlas-of-Number-Theory-in-Lean--Analytic-Number-Theory--Dirichlet___s-theorem-on-primes-in-arithmetic-progressions--Dirichlet___s-theorem-on-primes-in-arithmetic-progressions":{"contents":"(Dirichlet's theorem.) Let  be a positive integer and  a unit.\nThen the set of primes  with  is infinite:\n\nIn particular every residue class coprime to the modulus contains infinitely many primes.\n\nmathlib proves the contrapositive (by_contra): if the prime set were finite, then the sum of\n over that residue class restricted to primes would be summable; but the deep input\nnot_summable_residueClass_prime_div shows this sum diverges. That divergence is assembled from the\nanalytic theory: the indicator of the residue class is written via orthogonality of Dirichlet\ncharacters () as ,\nso  becomes a character-weighted combination of the logarithmic\nderivatives  (). An auxiliary function\nsubtracts the pole term  coming from the trivial character and is shown to\nextend continuously to the closed half-plane \n(continuousOn_LFunctionResidueClassAux); this continuity rests precisely on the non-vanishing of the\n-functions there (, ), since\na zero would create a logarithmic pole. The non-prime prime-power contribution converges\n(summable_residueClass_non_primes_div), so the prime part must carry the divergence, contradicting\nfiniteness.\n\n","context":"AINTLIB — An Atlas of Number Theory in Lean\u0009Analytic Number Theory\u0009Dirichlet's theorem on primes in arithmetic progressions","header":"2.7.1. Dirichlet's theorem on primes in arithmetic progressions","id":"/Analytic-Number-Theory/Dirichlet___s-theorem-on-primes-in-arithmetic-progressions/#AINTLIB-___-An-Atlas-of-Number-Theory-in-Lean--Analytic-Number-Theory--Dirichlet___s-theorem-on-primes-in-arithmetic-progressions--Dirichlet___s-theorem-on-primes-in-arithmetic-progressions"},"/Analytic-Number-Theory/The-Riemann-zeta-function/#AINTLIB-___-An-Atlas-of-Number-Theory-in-Lean--Analytic-Number-Theory--The-Riemann-zeta-function--The-L-series-of-an-arithmetic-function":{"contents":"For a function , the -series (Dirichlet series) of  is\n\nwhere the -th term LSeries.term f s n is  for  and  for . The\nseries is evaluated wherever it converges absolutely (LSeriesSummable); below the abscissa of\nabsolute convergence mathlib sets its value to . The Riemann zeta function, the Dirichlet\n-functions, and the -series of the von Mangoldt function are all instances.\n\n","context":"AINTLIB — An Atlas of Number Theory in Lean\u0009Analytic Number Theory\u0009The Riemann zeta function","header":"2.1.1. The L-series of an arithmetic function","id":"/Analytic-Number-Theory/The-Riemann-zeta-function/#AINTLIB-___-An-Atlas-of-Number-Theory-in-Lean--Analytic-Number-Theory--The-Riemann-zeta-function--The-L-series-of-an-arithmetic-function"},"/Diophantine-Equations-and-Transcendence/Pell___s-equation___-its-solution-group___-and-the-fundamental-solution/#AINTLIB-___-An-Atlas-of-Number-Theory-in-Lean--Diophantine-Equations-and-Transcendence--Pell___s-equation___-its-solution-group___-and-the-fundamental-solution--Existence-of-Nontrivial-Pell-Solutions":{"contents":"If  is not a perfect square, then the equation  has a solution with\n.\n\nSet , which is irrational because  is a non-square integer\n(irrational_nrt_of_notint_nrt). Fix an integer . Using the infinitude of good\nrational approximations to  (), the set of rationals  with\n is infinite. Hence some fixed nonzero value \n() is attained on an infinite set \n(otherwise the union over  of finite sets would be finite). Mapping each such  to\n,\nthe pigeonhole principle (exists_ne_map_eq_of_mapsTo) produces two distinct  with the\nsame residues. The Brahmagupta composition then makes\n\nan integer pair (the numerators are divisible by  by the matching residues) solving\n (), with  since . The full\nequivalence — a nontrivial solution exists iff  is not a square — is\nPell.exists_iff_not_isSquare.\n\n","context":"AINTLIB — An Atlas of Number Theory in Lean\u0009Diophantine Equations and Transcendence\u0009Pell's equation, its solution group, and the fundamental solution","header":"9.4.4. Existence of Nontrivial Pell Solutions","id":"/Diophantine-Equations-and-Transcendence/Pell___s-equation___-its-solution-group___-and-the-fundamental-solution/#AINTLIB-___-An-Atlas-of-Number-Theory-in-Lean--Diophantine-Equations-and-Transcendence--Pell___s-equation___-its-solution-group___-and-the-fundamental-solution--Existence-of-Nontrivial-Pell-Solutions"}});